    align:confidence "0.85"^^xsd:float ;
    align:rationale "Both concepts refer to the process of making an AI system available for use. The dpv-ai concept explicitly mentions installation, release and configuration *within* a deployment stage, suggesting it's slightly more detailed than the AIDOC definition which focuses on delivery to production. They are highly similar but not interchangeable across all contexts."^^xsd:string ;
    align:relation skos:closeMatch ;
    align:source aidoc:Deployment ;
    align:target <https://w3id.org/dpv/ai#DeploymentStage> .

align:9282ed38-4e97-4dd2-9069-8f50fa5eb015 a prov:Entity,
        align:Mapping ;
    prov:wasAttributedTo align:LLMAlignmentBot ;
    prov:wasGeneratedBy align:402bfd97-c4c2-4676-bf34-dbb149e6db7d ;
    align:confidence "0.95"^^xsd:float ;
    align:rationale "The dpv-ai concept explicitly incorporates and combines definitions from multiple authoritative sources (ISO/IEC, OECD, EU) while the AIDOC definition is a single formulation. However, the core meaning – a machine-based system inferring outputs to influence environments with varying autonomy and adaptiveness – is identical. The lexical similarity score of 1.0 confirms this high degree of overlap."^^xsd:string ;
    align:relation skos:exactMatch ;
    align:source aidoc:AISystem ;
    align:target <https://w3id.org/dpv/ai#AISystem> .

align:a543039a-57fd-4e43-8a9b-541a5aa98eeb a prov:Entity,
